## Risks and Dependencies

| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| Phase III requires Phase II RBAC production-grade before attestation can begin | High | Approval workflows and role separation are Phase II P0 items — Phase III does not start until these ship |
| CSA STAR for AI certification timeline is an external dependency | Medium | ~80% of compliance layer is internally developed — platform work proceeds ahead of formal certification publication |
| PQC library maturity (Phase IV) | Low | CRYSTALS-Kyber and Dilithium are NIST-finalized; integration complexity is known, algorithm instability is not a risk |
| Defense procurement cycle length (Phase IV DoD alignment) | High | Patent portfolio and CSA contributions establish prior art and standards credibility — these are the procurement entry points, not cold outreach |
| Architecture concentration risk (Phases III–IV) | High | Published framework, patent filings, and CSA deliverables are the knowledge transfer and IP protection mechanism |

---

## About This Roadmap

AEGIS-X was not built to be a dashboard. It was built to be the governance infrastructure layer that autonomous compute systems require but the industry has not yet delivered.

Phase II is the product management entry point — the governance dashboard that makes the platform visible and usable to compliance stakeholders today. Phases III and IV are the architectural destination: a cryptographically sound, quantum-resistant, continuously attesting governance fabric for autonomous AI systems operating in regulated and defense environments.

The market will arrive at this destination. The only variable is whether organizations arrive on infrastructure they controlled from the beginning, or infrastructure they had to adopt reactively under regulatory pressure.

